sentences: In 2016, Chapman celebrated fifty years as a professional musician.
He first appeared on the London and Cornwall folk music circuits in 1967, including the Piper's Folk Club in Penzance, alongside John Martyn and Roy Harper.
His first album was Rainmaker in 1969.

The new century saw Chapman exploring his guitar player roots and releasing instrumental albums alongside his song-based sets.
The late 1990s onwards represented a period of continued rebirth for Chapman.
Chapman and Kemp used the album's title for a band in the mid 1980s.

Rainmaker was released on the EMI progressive label Harvest, and Chapman played the folk and progressive circuits during the festivals of the early 1970s, with Mick Ronson, Rick Kemp and Keef Hartley.
He became well known in the folk clubs of the late 1960s, as well as on the 'progressive' music scene, and released over 50 albums.

sentences: Michael Chapman (24 January 1941 – 10 September 2021) was an English singer-songwriter, and virtuosic guitar player.
In 2016, Chapman celebrated fifty years as a professional musician.
The record producer Don Nix worked on the album Savage Amusement, which included several songs from the past.
1977 saw the end of Chapman's Decca deal, and the beginning of an association with Criminal Records in 1978 and the two labels produced versions of The Man Who Hated Mornings.
He continued to make recordings that straddled musical genres and pushed his guitar playing to the fore, but had neither the profile nor sales of the previous decade.
Chapman released albums about every two years, receiving praise but without great sales, ending with the 1997 release Dreaming Out Loud.
"I had an art college education and on a rainy night in 1966 I went into a pub in Cornwall, but I couldn't afford to pay to go in.
So I said, I'll tell you what, I don't want to stay outside in the rain, I'll play guitar for half an hour for you.
They offered me a job for the rest of the summer and I've been at it ever since.
